### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input: Voltaire and Leila are vloggers, Voltaire has an average of 50 viewers per day while Leila has twice the number of viewers Voltaire has. They'll earn money, but they also have to work.<n><n>______ 27: I can't believe I got 3rd place in the math competition! I can't believe the girl who won said she didn't study at all. Each car can take 5 students. There is a total of 40 students from the class but there are still 10 students left over. How many students are in the whole class? (Let the number of students be 'n'. The cars can take, 'a5' students each. Also 'a' is equal to 10).<n><n>n+a5=40<n>a(n-10)=40<n>a=4<n>n=20<n><n>How many cars are there?<n><n># Challenge:<n>1. How many animals can you name?<n>2. B: 그것을 먹어 앞뒤를 1000m 앞돌아간 예요.<n><n># 출력 : B<n><n># 2 x 3 = 211<n># 40 - (150 - 40) = 50<n># 10 x 3 = 30<n># 3 x 3 = 9<n># 15 x 3 = 45<n># 2/3 * 4 = 6<n># 7 x 3 = 6<n># [20/2] * [5/2] = 140<n># [4/2] * [12/4] * 4 = 140 <n><n># 50 / 2 = 25<n># 140 + 25 = 165<n># 2 / 2 = 1<n># 4 * 2 = 8<n># 40 / 100 = 1/5<n># [4/3] * [10/10] = 18

If 3 people are seated in First Class, 5 people are seated in business class and 16 people are seated in economy class, how many economy class passengers and how many passengers overall are on board?<n>Output:70,85<n>  Solution:<n>Input:Let the number of people in business class = a<n>The number of people in first class = b<n>The number of people are seated in an economy class = c<n>We know that b, a and c is number of people in business, first and economy class respectively. So c=16+a+b. This can be represented as(c)=a+b<n>And the number of people overall = 47+c. So<n>47+c = b<n>Solving this will 47=b+c<n>And c=b+16<n>Solving this<n>53=b+16. This will be in form of b=53-16.<n>The number of overall people = 47+53-16=287<n>The no. Of people in an economy class 28

How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. If they earn $0.50 per view, how much does Leila earn per week?<n>Output: 350<n><n>Input:An attempt to confirm an applicant's reference would fail if the reference does what? Choices:  A: question B: dispute C: deny D: contradict E: refuse<n>Output:		C<n>The correct answer is letter B.<n><n># Solution<n>## BFS<n>- The idea of BFS is to start from each vertex and find the shortest path to the destination.<n>- In the given problem, find the shortest path (destination) vertex from each vertex to (target) vertex.<n>- Add the `Vertex` objects to the `list` in the queue.<n>- While traversing the graph:<n>- Create a new `pathFinder` and `queue` to track the shortest path to each vertex (from the `rootVertex`).<n>- Check if a `Vertex` in the `queue` has an empty string.<n>- If there are no more `Vertex` objects in this `pathFinder`, print the shortest path.

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. For every 3 t-shirts she buys, she gets 1 free t-shirt. Martha decides to buy 4 jackets and 9 t-shirts. How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input: Voltaire and Leila are vloggers, Voltaire has an average of 50 viewers per day while Leila has twice the number of viewers Voltaire has. If they earn $0.50 per view, how much does Leila earn per week?<n>Output: 350<n><n>Input:Where would you stand in a line and need a coat if it is cold? Choices:  A: graph B: bank at noon C: good book D: post office E: bus stop<n>Output:		C<n><n>### Solution<n><n>For the first problem.<n><n>We can assume without loss of generalty that there are 4 cards left for maria. <n>In addition to the 35 cards leftover for Janet and Brenda, we need 8 more cards for Janet to have 43. If we assume the number of cards Janet has is 43, then if maria has 43 - 43, we have Janet's number as well.<n>43 - 37 = 6 is the solution<n><n>For the second problem. <n>We know Janet's total is from the first problem (lets call it J).<n>We can calculate for the 40 missing.<n>4 * J = 280. <n>So Brenda's total is 211.<n><n>For the third problem,<n>we can set up the following.<n><n>Let there be B of green, B of blue and W of White. <n>W = B + 3G<n><n>W - B = 13<n><n>Let J = 3G<n><n>J + G =11<n><n>Let x = G<n><n>Solving for W, W = 50.<n><n>For the fourth problem, we need to set up a similar system.<n>Let X = Alannah books.<n><n>Alannah has 2 more books<n><n>Let P = 2<n><n>Q = Alannah + Beatrix<n><n>Q - P = 28<n><n>Let D = 1Q<n><n>D + X = 40<n><n>So, books = 160.<n><n>For this one, I think the trick is knowing the order of magnitude. <n>We are told the difference is 17, the given book quantity is 52, and there are 5 birds. If the numbers are between 0-20, then we are working with a 9-24. <n><n>We know the answer is 18. <n>52 * (9/22) = 18 * 0.3. <n><n>Lets assume for these cases that<n><n>We have 5 birds, with 5 berries<n>We assume 6 birds with 6 berries<n><n>If its 6 birds, this is equivalent to a little over 3 berries per

The output should be:<n><n>```html<n>(10, 10, 99, 10)<n>```<n>The following code will be in your assignment:<n>```html<n>  # Your code goes here<n>  import sys<n>  def convertToDict(string of values):<n>      resultDict = [('10', '10', '99', '10')]<n>      numbers = string.split(',')<n>      print(string)<n>      convertNumberToDict = str(numbers).replace(' ', '')<n>      convertNumberToInts = list(convertNumberToDict)<n>      if len(convertNumberToInts) == 2:<n>          return 'No values'<n>      for i in range(len(convertNumberToInt (Ints ):<n>          for i in range(1, len(convertNumberToDict)):<n>              if i%2!= 0:<n>                  resultDict.append(('{}, {:,}'.format(convertNumberToDict, i)))<n>              if i% 2 == 0:<n>                   resultDict.append(convertNumberToDict**<n>```<n><n>## 3<n><n>Problem:<n>You are provided a dictionary and have to write recursive code that counts all of the apples inside the dictionary.<n><n>```html<n>  def apples():<n>      count = 0<n>      for item in fruit:<n>          if item['type'] == 'apple':

You're more likely to get a hair brush from your house. -Hospitals don't sell bandages. -If you are not sure what band-aid is, then choose D.<n>-Drugstore is the right place to get hairbrush and bandagas.<n>

How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. For every 3 t-shirts she buys, she gets 1 free t-shirt. Martha decides to buy 4 jackets and 9 t-shirts. How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input: Voltaire and Leila are vloggers, Voltaire has an average of 50 viewers per day while Leila has twice the number of viewers Voltaire has. If they earn $0.50 per view, how much does Leila earn per week?<n>Output: 350<n><n>Input:The fact the two sides were able to even reach tentative agreement was a feat to what? Choices:  A: accomplish B: make progress C: stop arguing D: do business E: concert<n>Output:		A<n><n>### Solution:<n> <n>```python<n> <n>import sys<n>import pprint<n>from collections import Counter<n><n>def solution(text, i, i_end, n, n_end):<n>    <n>    if text[i_end] == " " and n == 0:<n>        d = {Counter.from_list(list(text)).most_common()[-1].items()}<n>        return str(d.popitem()[0] + d.popitem()[1])<n>        <n>    elif n == 0:     <n>        d = { text[i_end].upper() + text[i_end - 1].upper(): 1 } <n>        return str(counter.get(text[i_end].lower(), {}).get("most", 0) + counter.get(text[l_end-1].lower(), {}).pop("most", 0))<n>        <n>    <n>    if not n:  <n>        d = { " " + text[i] : 1 for i in range(0,len(text[0])) }<n>        return str(max(d.items()))<n>        <n> <n>    else:  <n>        n -= 1    # the length needs to be decreased by 1 to take account of the fact that the 9th and the 10th digit are taken.<n>        if i < n_end:    # the length of digit needs to be increased once we can't get the 10th<n>            n += 1   <n>        d = { str({Counter.from_list([text[i].strip()]) if text[i].strip() in text[i_end-1].strip() else []}) + text[i]:1 for i in range (0,n+1) }<n>        return max(d.items())<n>```<n><n>

Each child gets the same number of apples. 1.How many apples does each child get in this case?  A.2 apples B.3 apples C.4 apples D.6 apples 2.If a child chooses apple A, the total number of apples will be _________. A.4 B.2 C.6 D.3<n>Output: D<n><n>Input: <n>There are 4 apples. There is 1 apple for each of the 4 children.How many apples does child 1 have?<n>Output: <n>A.3 B.4 C.2 D.1<n><n>Output: B<n>Input: <n>A.<n>B.<n>C.<n>D.<n>Output: <n>D<n>Input: <n>B.<n>C<n>D<n>Output: <n>C<n><n>Input:<n><n>```python<n>import math<n>import sys<n><n>def solution(input):<n>    # Write your code in Python<n>    answer = 0<n>    for c in range(5, 0, -1):<n>        #if input[0]!= c:<n>        if len(input) == 4:<n>            return(answer + int(input[1])*c)<n>        else:<n>            answer += int(input[0])*c<n>            return(answer)<n><n>def solvePart1():<n>    input = sys.stdin.readline().rstrip("\n")<n>    input = input.split()<n>    final = solution(input)<n>    print(final)<n>    return<n><n># Driver Code<n>solvePart1()<n>```<n><n>Input:<n>```<n>5.<n>6<n>9<n>17<n>6<n>18<n>26<n>6<n>```<n>Output:<n>```63```<n>

How many pairs of counters can make if each pair consists of at least 2 counters of the same color?<n>Output: 8<n><n>Input: There is a 1x7 tableau. We take turns placing counters on the tableau in one of three moves: (1) we can place 1 counter on an empty cell; (2) we can place 2 counters on a single cell; and (3) we can place a single counter onto an existing pair of counters. It can’t go directly on the existing pair.<n><n>We begin play with three counters of the same type, and a 7-counters of the other type. Each player chooses a type and takes their turn placing all of their given counters on the tableaux (if this is not possible, the turn is skipped). The first player to place all of their counters wins; in the event of a draw, the players continue play with different types.<n>Input: The tableau is:<n><n>You are blue: 2 counters<n>You are orange: 7 counters and 3 open cells<n>You go first<n>Output: blue wins.<n><n>Input: Ants have 7 legs, grasshoppers have 6 legs, and roaches have 8 legs. Let's look at some examples to get a quick idea of subtraction.<n><n>5 – 3 = 2<n>2 -7 = -5<n><n>Subtraction rules<n>• The signs are always subtracted, not added. To illustrate, subtract 1 from 4 and you get 3 (not 2).<n>• The sign of the answer always stays the same. To illustrate, if you subtract 3 from 13, the answer will be negative, never positive.<n>As you might have noticed, whenever you subtract a number from itself, the answer is always zero. To illustrate,<n>1 - 1 = 0, 2 - 2 = 0, and so on. Whenever you subtract a number from another number and the answer is 0, you don't have to write it. If they earn $0.50 per view, how much does Leila earn per week?<n>Output: 350<n><n>Input:The woman experienced great joy, but despite that this was a what? Choices:  A: misery B: sadness C: bad time D: sorrow E: play time<n>Output:		 A<n><n>Input:The boy wants a ride _____ and went to his friend's house every day. He always played, but some days he rode more; sometimes he didn't ride at all. How many times did he ride in all?<n>Output:"<n>A:16<n>B: 17<n>C: 19<n>D: 20<n><n>E:21"""<n><n><n>#input list:1,3,6<n>#output list:2,4,7<n>nums = [int(num) for num in input()]<n>stack = []<n>result = 0<n><n>for i in range(len(nums)):<n>    if nums[i]>0:<n>        stack.append(nums[i])<n>    else:<n>        res = 0<n>        while stack:<n>            num = stack.pop(0)<n>            res = num + res<n>            if 1 == num:<n>                break<n>        return result + res<n>        <n>        <n>

Which student is speaking?<n>Output: A student B<n><n># Your Solution Below<n>```<n>def number_of_days_between(start_date, end_date):<n>    """<n>    Return the number of days between the dates passed in.<n>    """<n>    # your code here<n>    days = end_date.month - start_date.month<n>    if start_date.day == end_date.day:<n>        return days<n>    if start_data.day > end_date.day or end_date.day > start_date.day: <n>        days = end_date - start_date<n>    return days<n>```<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. If they earn $0.50 per view, how much does Leila earn per week?<n>Output: 350<n><n>Input:If you're standing in line and the line isn't moving what might you feel? He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. For every 3 t-shirts she buys, she gets 1 free t-shirt. Martha decides to buy 4 jackets and 9 t-shirts. How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input: Voltaire and Leila are vloggers, Voltaire has an average of 50 viewers per day while Leila has twice the number of viewers Voltaire has. If they earn $0.50 per view, how much does Leila earn per week?<n>Output: 350<n><n>Input:What are people playing when they want to take the lead with small papers? Choices:  A: very heavy B: video game C: news article D: card game E: lead pencil<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: What are 5+2?Choices:  A: 10 B: 7 C: 6 D: 5 E: 4<n>Output: B<n><n>Input: What color is the apple? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. For every 3 t-shirts she buys, she gets 1 free t-shirt. Martha decides to buy 4 jackets and 9 t-shirts. How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input: Voltaire and Leila are vloggers, Voltaire has an average of 50 viewers per day while Leila has twice the number of viewers Voltaire has. If they earn $0.50 per view, how much does Leila earn per week?<n>Output: 350<n><n>Input:I wanted  a side chair for people to visit me while I worked, where did I have it put? Choices:  A: building B: office C: library D: table E: bathtub<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: I wanted  a side chair  for people to visit me  while I worked Choices: A: building B:  office C: library D : table E :  bathtub<n>Output E : bathtub<n><n>Input: I went to the park, where did I go next? Choices:  C: playground D: picnic area<n>Output:  C : park<n><n>Input:How wide of a table are you getting? Choices:  F: 6 feet G:  1 foot<n>Output:  F 6 feet<n><n>Input:Maria has three times as many apples as oranges and the oranges are 8 times as many as bananas. He has a total of 27 apples, 12 oranges, and 8 bananas altogether. How many apples did Maria start with?<n>Output: 8 oranges<n><n># Multiple answers for question!<n><n># Input:<n>classroom_chairs = 10<n>blue_chairs = 4.5 * 10<n>green_chairs = 3 * blue_chairs<n>white_chairs = 5 * green_chairs<n>total = blue_chairs + (green_chairs * 5/10) + white_chairs<n>answer = total<n><n># Output:<n># classroom_chairs = blue_chairs<n># classroom_color = green_chairs<n># answer = green_chairs - blue_chairs<n>my_colors = 'green', 'white','blue'<n>total_count = 50<n><n><n><n><n>my_colors.append(total_count)<n>answer = total_count<n><n>answer1 = 4.5 + 3<n>answer2 = 3 * (13/18)<n>t_count = answer1 + answer2<n><n>answer = t_count<n>answer_t = 'blue','green','white'<n>t_count = 4 * 3<n>answer_t[0] = round(t_count, 2)<n>answer = answer_t<n><n>answer = 6 * 3<n>answer = total + total/6<n>answer = 'blue','green'<n><n># Answer <n><n># Input: Alannah,Batricia,150<n>answer1 = 150/18

Then we see the next step in the problem with 2+3=5. It would be 5+3=8 but there is an additional +2 so we have the number 8 +2+3=11.

B: A - B =?<n>    Answer A<n><n>### Question3: Question: Answer following multiple- choice question.<n><n>### Constructing Expressions<n><n>In mathematics, we often have to perform operations on quantities that cannot be performed directly. For example, we cannot divide 2 by -3 because division is always done by taking the reciprocal, which in this case is 6/3. A subtrahend is a number or quantity from which something else is subtracted; a minuend is the number or quantity from which a subtraction is performed. As an example, we have the following subtraction: 7 - 40 = - 33. In this case, we have a minuend of 7 and a subtrahend of 40. The 33 obtained refers to the subtraction.<n><n>Addition: We often find that the sum of two numbers can be obtained, but not all the time or in any situation. Given two numbers, the sum may be found if and only if the addition of two numbers is defined. For example, to find the sum of 3 and 4 we simply add an additive notation of (3+4). The same is true when 5 and 4 are added. To find the sum of 17 + 22, to find the sum, we first have to perform the addition of all the digits of 17 and 22, and then obtain a product of that sum: 17+22 = 55, which is a product of

We know that Janet has 21 more than Brenda and 26 more than Mara. So now lets calculate the total number of cards.<n><n>Their number of card we have to add to the initial number of cards that is 62.<n><n>So finally the total number of cards from the two cases (if Janet's number of cards is smaller than her's then we sum those cards with initial number otherwise we just sum the initial number with additional number of cards)<n><n>So the second part of the question is to choose between having 20 and 40 blocks that pete has walked<n><n>Again initial number we can use as 21 since

We have to put 5 mushrooms per pound of pizza sauce left. How many boxes have to be filled?<n>Output: 8<n><n>Input: Janine drives 11 miles to the library. She goes 2 miles for the books. How many miles did she walk?<n>Output: 9<n><n>### Explanation of Solution<n>```python<n>def solution(input):<n>    number = 0<n>    for char in input:<n>        if char == "+" or char == "×" or char == "=" or char == "=":<n>            number=((number*11)%(10)) if char == "+" else (number*(11-1)*11)%10<n>        elif char == "+":<n>            number=((int(input[:-1])*11)%19)<n>        elif char == "×":<n>            if(int(input[:-3])%3 == int(input[:-2])-int(input[:-2:])!=1):<n>                number = ((((int(input[:1])-input[1:3])*11) %19) / 9)<n>            else:<n>                number = (int(input[:15])*11 %19)/9<n>        elif char == "-":<n>            number = ((int(input[:2])*11) if int(input[-2]) == int(input[-1]) % 10) % 19-11<n>        elif char == "*":<n>            number = (int(str(input[:1])) if int(input[-1:]) in "012" else 11*11)<n>        elif char.isdigit():<n>            number = 11*(11*(11 if int(input[:1])==11 else 1) if int(str("".join(["0"+input[-1:1] if int(input[-(2:-1):1]) == 2 else "2"+input[(1:-1):1]])))/9 == 1 else 1/9)*11)*11<n>        else:<n>            return 0<n>    return str

What is the ratio between boys and girls? <n>Output: Boys:Girls 5:4<n><n>Instructions:<n>Input and Output should be in string format only.<n><n>Instructions for the user:<n>For any queries or suggestions please leave a comment below.<n>https://www.codechef.com/JULY19QR/results <n><n>import re # import re for regex<n><n>class Solution:<n>    def checkNumberRange(s):<n>        if re.match('^[1-9][0-9]+$',s) :<n>            if s<10000 or s>999999:<n>                return False,re.findall('\d+', s)<n>            else:<n>                return True,[]<n>        else:<n>            return False,[]<n><n>def addDigits(value,digits=3):<n>    if value>=19:<n>        result=str(value/10)<n>        return addDigits(value%10,digits-1)<n>    else:<n>        return result<n><n>def calcMod(value,digits):<n>    modulus=1<n>    for i in range(1,digits+1):<n>        modulus=modulus*10<n>    modulus=modulus**1<n>

If you were to paint one of each color, 5 apples should have the same number of each type of piece as 12 grapes. How many pieces do you need to paint the apples and grapes?<n>Output:20<n><n>Input:John ate 3/4 of his pie at a wedding and another 1/5 at a picnic. If John has 4 pie pieces left over, how many did John eat at the picnic?<n>Output:1/10<n><n>Input:Alice baked a cake and cut it into 8 slices. A 14 slice of leftovers was made. What is the total amount of cake leftover if each slice weighs 1 1/2 pounds?<n>Output:10/7<n><n>Input:Eva and Julia ate 3/5 of 7/10 of a pie. If they ate 4/5 of 10/15, how many slices of pie were there left?<n>Output:1<n><n>Input:Carol made a pot of soup. She drank 3/4 of the pot. She then divided her soup between Paul and Marissa. If they each have 1 1/5 of the pot, what fraction is left in the pot?<n><n>Output:3/10<n><n>#### Solution:<n>```python<n><n>a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h,i,j = map(int,input().split())<n><n>if a!=b:<n>    diff=b-a<n>    print(diff)<n>elif a!=c:<n>    diff=c-a<n>    print()<n>    diff=diff-1<n>    print(diff+1)<n>    print(diff*1/10)<n>elif sum(range(a,b+1))==(b-a)*1/10:<n>    sum=0<n>    counter=0<n>    print(sum)<n>    for i in range(b,a,-1):<n>        sum+=i<n>        counter+=1<n>        print(sum)<n>print(sum/counter)    <n><n><n><n><n>```<n>

NGC 4414<n>Answer: 4<n>In 2004, astronomers discovered a galaxy 10 billion light years from Earth. It is now known to be one of the most massive galaxies in the Universe, more massive than the Milky Way.<n>A: M33 B: NGC 2844 C: NGC 922 D: NGC 4415 E: NGC 4438<n><n>It is commonly accepted that galaxies formed in the early universe. It is assumed that galaxies formed as dense concentrations of gas cooled and collapsed under the pull of gravity. It is believed that small proto-galaxies merged to form massive galaxies, like the Milky Way. For many years, that's what everyone thought happened. But there were a few problems with this paradigm.<n><n>One problem was that the Universe wasn't big enough: the Universe was thought to be about 10 billion light-years from edge to edge. Such a small Universe would not allow enough time for a significant number of galaxy mergers.<n>A large primordial galaxy would be hard to explain if we did not take the Big Bang itself into account. In a Universe that is 10 billion years old, very few significant mergers would take place, but in a Universe with a 14 billion year history, the amount of merging possible is significantly higher.<n><n>NGC 4414, a massive primordial galaxy at z = 2.9, is located near the North Celestial Pole. NGC 4431.7 lies 3.4 degrees south of 12 hours to the south. NGC 4459 is located in the constellation Corvus and is the largest known primal galaxy in the CSF survey to date.<n><n><n>Input:The temperature at which water becomes ice, called the freezing point, is equal to the boiling point at 4 degrees Celsius.<n><n>You are told that the freezing point of water<n>is 9 degrees Celsius. How many times will the following string repeat?<n><n>A(B*D)<n><n>## 08. Write a program to check if a string is a valid base case for factorial.<n><n>```<n>#!/usr/bin/env python<n>import sys<n>import math<n><n>def factorial(a):<n>    if (a == 0):<n>        return 1<n>    if (a < 0):<n>        print("Error: negative factorial")<n>    for b in range(1,a+1):<n>    return a * b<n>def string_to_array(s):<n>    arr = []<n>    for x in s:<n>        arr.append(int(x))<n>    return arr<n>def check_validity(string_arr,num_base):<n>    if len(string_arr) <= num_base:<n>        print("valid")<n>    else:<n>        print("invalid")<n>check_validity(string(0),2)<n>print("base 2 is invalid ")<n>check_validity("".join(str(i) for i in range(2,21,2)),2)<n>print("valid")<n>print("base 3 is valid")<n>check_valid(string_to_array("AB"),2)<n>print("invalid")<n>```<n><n>## 07. 1 and 4 are base case; 11 and 243 are not base case.<n><n>```<n>input: A(B*C)<n>Output: 1<n><n>input: A(1-B)(C-D)<n>Output: 4<n><n>input: A(-B*C+D)<n>Output:11<n><n>input: (A^B-C+D)<n>output:

How long after Amy gets ready, does Lina arrive at school?<n>Output: Lina arrive at school 43 minutes after Amy got ready.<n><n>##### Submit<n>```Python<n>from math import *<n>while True:<n>    question, answer = input().split()<n>    <n>    if question == "":<n>        break<n>    <n>    number_of_guesses = 0<n>    guessed_letter = guess_random_letter(answer)<n>    print(guessed_letter)<n>    guessed_score = score_letter_by_number(guessed_letter, answer[1])<n>    new_guess = input()<n>    <n>    while new_guess not in ['#']:<n>        if new_guess == guessed_letter and guessed_score == guessed_letter:<n>            print("Congratulations!")<n>            print("You are right!")<n>            break<n>        <n>        if number_of_guess == 6:<n>            print("Oops, guess again!")<n>            break <n>        number_of_guests += 1<n>        <n>        #check condition and increment number of guesses<n>        if new_letter not in answer:<n>            if len(new_letters) > 1:<n>                guessed_score = 500<n>            else: <n>                guessed_letter = new_letter<n>                guessed_number = 1<n>

Choices:  A: public building B: tomb C: arena D: large building E: treasure<n>Output:		B<n><n><n><n>import dataStructures<n><n>#Solution1:<n><n>def answer():<n>    #reading input<n>    num_of_questions = int(input('Number of questions: '))<n><n><n>    print("------------------Multiple Choice Questions----------------")<n>    for _ in range(num_of_questions):<n>        #multiple choice questions<n>        numOfInput = int(input('How many cards do they have all together? '))<n>        if numOfInput == 211:<n>            print('Incorrect, the num of cards is'+ str(211))<n>        elif numOfInput == 40:<n>            print('Correct, the num of cards are'+ str(40))<n>        else:<n>            print('Invalid input')<n><n><n>    print('')<n>    print("----------------------------------------------------")<n><n>    print("Entering Data Structure Class")<n>    print("-----------------------")<n><n>    class ListNode:<n>        def __init__(self, data=None, next=None):<n>            self.val = data<n>            self.next = next<n><n>        def append(self, data):<n>            Node = ListNode(data)<n>            if self.next == None:<n>                self.next = Node<n>            else:<n>                self.last.next = Node<n>                self.last = Node<n><n>        def length(self):<n>            newnode = self.last<n>            len = 0<n>            while True:<n>                len = len + 1<n>                if not newnode:<n>                    return len<n>                newnode = newnode.next<n><n><n>#enter code here<n>import math<n><n>num = 5<n>max = num + 2<n>new = ListNode(num)<n><n>def lengthOfList(head):<n>    return 1<n><n>    def main():<n>        answer()<n><n>if __name__ == '__main__':<n>    main()<n>

Choices:  A: compliments B: understand themselves C: life partner D: second chances E: larger house<n>Output:		A<n><n><n>#### Instruction 2: What you should do is create or copy and paste the code below :<n><n>import sys<n><n>answer = sys.argv[1]<n>if answer == 'Houston':<n>    answer = 50<n>if answer == 'Same':<n>    answer = sum(sys.argv[2:])<n>if answer =='Wall':<n>    answer = min(sys.argv[1:])<n>if answer=='Yes':<n>    answer = int(sys.argv[3:])*3<n>if answer =='No':<n>    answer = sys.argv[3:] - 3<n>if answer == 'Church':<n>    answer = list(zip(sys.argv[:3], sys.argv[3:]))[0]<n>if answer =='Yes I do!':<n>    if len(sys.argv) ==3 or len(sys.argv)=2:<n>        choice=len(sys.argv)<3<n>        answer = choice<n>if answer=='No you dont':<n>    if len (sys.argv) == 2:<n>        choice = len(sys.argv<2)<n>        answer = choice <n>if answer=='Not Sure':<n>    answer = sorted(input('Please enter a number: '))<n><n>sys.stdout.write(str(answer)+'\n')<n><n><n>#### Instructions: After you are finished typing all of your code, please hit enter 4 times. Now type the following 4 commands:<n><n>>>>> <n><n>#### Instrucction 2: You may wish to save your work to your personal drive for your own records.

Marra has twice as many cards more than Janet.<n>So Brenda has 10 Cards less than Mara.<n><n>Now: Janet's cards = 150, Brenda's cards = 9.<n><n>Thus, Janet's cards - 9 = 141.<n><n>Mara's cards = 2*141 = 282<n><n>Subtracting from 150: 150 - (141 + 282) = 48.Thus, Mara has 48 cards more than Brenda<n><n>Case 2:<n><n>Output:<n>Pete is 50 blocks away from Garage.<n>After riding a bus for 20 blocks,<n>The distance Pete covered = 30 blocks<n>The number of blocks Pete travelled in all = 50 + 30 = 80 blocks.<n><n>Case 3:<n><n>Output:There are 10 blue Chairs.<n>10 Blue + 3 Green + 13 White = 26<n>Thus, Number of chairs in the classroom = 26+10 = 36<n><n>Case 4:<n><n>Output:3 pints of coffee<n><n>Case 5:<n><n>Output:130 books<n><n>Case 6:

The ratio of men to women become 9:16. How many women were in the original group of 90?<n>Output:60<n>---<n><n>### What are the 6 different methods you can use to solve a system of inequalities?<n><n>1.Graphing a system of inequalites<n>2.Algebraic solutions<n>3.Square Root Bounds<n>4.Test Points<n>5.Division and Subtraction<n>6.Solutions Set and Inequality Set<n><n>---<n><n>## Instruction:Answer the questions in the section below.<n><n>### How can you solve the problem using the methods listed above?<n>Input:There are 90 men and 45 women in a group and the men and women ratio are 3:4 respectively. 50 women leave the group, the men:women ratio becomes 9:16.How many women are in the original group of90?<n><n>I choose to solve this question with the graphical method listed above.<n><n>The graph shows that the inequality is open upwards because the blue points(men) are outside the boundary(2,3 4,6 ) as well as the green points(women). That is to say that the inequality x <=6 is satisfied because of the values of x are 0,1,2 which are all under 6.<n><n>Hence, the solution set is {0,1,2,3,4,5,6}<n><n>The solution set and inequality set is {0,2,4,5,7,9}<n><n>### How did you find your answer?<n><n>Graphing a system of inequality<n>This method requires a deep understanding of geometry, I have to be very precise in my drawing to be sure I get it right.<n>I start by drawing the boundary of the inequality. I do not only need to know how to draw points on the coordinate plane, I need to know how to use graph paper(graphical paper).<n><n>The next step is drawing the inequality sign(<=) and putting it where it should be in the graph.<n><n>After this I write down the solution set which is {0,1,2, 3, 4,

He wants to get back to where he started walking. How far has Bob walked?<n>Output: 4<n><n>### Solution<n>* Instructions: You may use a pencil and paper to assist you in solving the problems.<n>* Input: Janet has 22 cards more than Brenda's. Mara has twice Janet's number of cards so Brenda has half of Mara's number? How many cards do they all play?<n><n>### Solution for input 1: 211.<n>We can rewrite it like this:<n><n>`Janet has 9 cards - Brenda`<n><n>`Mara has twice as many cards - Janet`<n><n>To solve this, all we need to do now is to calculate:<n><n>`Janets Cards - Janet's cards * 2 = 211`<n><n>`Janet cards + Janet's cards = Janet's cards - 2?`<n><n>`26 = 210`<n><n>`20 = 18`<n><n>`80?`<n><n>`82 = 16`<n><n>`73 = 27`<n><n>`74 = 25`<n><n>By doing this way, we can get `211 as input.<n><n>### Solution, second part.<n><n>```<n>26 + 20 - 2 = 22<n>22 + 18 - 2 = 86<n>86 + 16 = 80<n>```<n><n>### Solution: Input 2<n>We have 2 cases in which, we can answer the question:<n><n>* Pete walked 5 block from Houston to bus garage.<n><n>The bus ride is `20 block`<n><n>The bus garages are located `X block` away from the destination.<n><n>### Example<n>In example 1, Houston is 0 block away. Thus, Pete can walk to bus garage by `25 block`.<n><n>```python<n>    Pete walks 5*15 -20 = 65 block. - 65 = 10 block<n>

Choices:  A: next to the house B: keeping things in C: backyard D: farm yard E: ranch<n>Output:		D<n><n>Input: How many 4 inch planks are needed for a 10 foot by 12 foot floor? Options:5 45 0 4<n>Output:45<n><n>Input: A car is traveling at a sustained speed of 10mph and slows down to 4mph every 5 seconds for a city of 100,000. When traveling at 5mph the car takes 0.3 mph off of that speed every 2s. When traveling at it maximum speed of 10 mph, the car loses 0.3 mps speed every 1.5 minutes. At what rate will the car be traveling when traveling at it maximum of speed of 3mph?<n>Output: 4.7mph<n><n>## Python code:<n>import sys<n><n>for _ in range(1):<n>    inpt = input()<n>    if inpt == "0":<n>        break<n>    inpt = inpt.split()<n>    answer, count = 0, 0<n>    for i, c in enumerate(inpt):<n>        if c == "?":<n>            count = count+1<n>        else:<n>            answer = int(answer) * int(c)<n>            inpt[i], inpt[i + count] = inpt[i + 1], ''<n>    print(count * answer)<n><n>```

The catalog lists the price of the article in figures followed by a period, then its price again in words. Example: "8.--$3.98" means that this item is priced at $3.98. In other words, $1.00 is the second digit. If, instead of $3.98, we see "3--98", that means that $2.97 is the second digit. Let's say that we see this notation for 17 of the prices. One day a sale starts. The sale allows us to multiply our discount by the price. Each of the 17 articles has a different discount. For example, we know that the 11th article will cost us $10.63. At the same time, the 5-item sale applies to the 10th article only. We know that it will cost us $2.20. This means that the 11 item is the last item to be sold at half price. Find the number of items that are still left.<n>Output: 6.5

You are allowed to use a rope to attach the box to a 70-kg man at the other end. The man has the choice to make sure that the balls remain on top of the box, or to tip the box over. If he chooses to tip, then the balls on top will spill. If you and the man are allowed to rearrange the balls however you wish, what is the maximum weight the box can bear?<n>Output: 75<n><n><n>Answers:<n>Answer 1:<n>There are 13 chairs.<n>The first statement is: "There are 10 blue cards".<n>The second statement is: "The green chairs are 2 times as many as the blued cards".<n>10x2 = 20, and 20 less than 13 = 11.<n>11 less than 9 cards than 150 is 59. 50+59 = 109 so Janet has 109 cards.<n><n>Answer 2:<n>There are 50 blocks.<n>The first statement says that Pete walked 5+20 = 25 blocks from home to the bus garage.<n><n>The second statement says that Pete rode the bus 2+10 = 12 blocks to the post office.<n><n>Answer 3:<n>There are 67 chairs in the classroom.<n>The first statement gives that there are 10 blues chairs.<n>The second statement gives 13 green chairs.<n>10+13 = 23.<n>3 blue times 23 = 69, and 1 blue leaves us with 5 green.<n>So 67 comes from 69 + 6 = 50 + 5 + 6.<n><n>Answer 4:<n>1 quart = 0.25 gallons.<n>6 pints = 0.5 gallons.<n>The first statement gave that there are 4.5 and 3, which comes to 7.5.<n>So 14 pints is the right answer.<n><n>Answer 5:<n>There are 268 books in all.<n>

The difference between the two numbers is 9, and the difference represents 9 cards, and so on.<n><n>Janet = Janet + 9 -150 = 211<n>Mara has twice as many cards than Janet, which means she has 80 more cards than Janet.<n><n>Brenda(Janet - 80) = Brenda + 80<n>Janet has 80 more than what Brenda(Janet -80)<n>Janet has 12 more cards than Brenda(Janet-80)<n><n>The total number of cards = 211+ Brenda(Janet+Janet-80-80 = 215 cards<n><n>The first question has the following instruction<n><n>In a classroom, there area blue chairs, green chair, and white chair. There are 16 blue chairs. The Green chairs are 3 more than the blue chairs. And there are 13 less white chairs than the Green and blue chairs combined<n><n>In the first part, we take the number of Blue chairs as B to be 16,<n>there are 3 Green chairs, add it to the 16 blue chair result in 18 chairs to represent the Green chairs, and there is 13 chairs less than the Green and Blue chairs combined.<n><n>The number of chairs = 16(B-13)+18(B+3) = 25<n><n>In the third problem, Alannah, Beatix and Queen got 110 books from their parents. Beatrix has 20 less books  than Alannah. Queen has 15 books, and Alannah gives Beatrix 3 books.<n><n>By subtracting the numbers given Alannah has 5 books, and there are two methods of finding the answer,<n><n>There are 5 less than Beatrix's books, plus 3 to Alannah = 2 books Alannah gets from Beatrix,<n>and so for 19 more than Beatrix and 16 more than Alannah's books<n><n>110-20+16+1(3)=1

Choices: B: none of these choices C: ate D: able E: abel<n>Output: E<n><n>## Explanation:<n><n>### Solution 1<n>```py<n>if Janet has 9 more cards than Brenda:<n>     Janet has more cards than Brenda, so Brenda has fewer cards than Jaeten.<n>```<n><n>```py<n>if Mara has twice as much cards as Janet:<n>    Janet's cards =228 <n>    Mara's cards = 114 + 60% of Janet's cards<n>    Janet' cards = 210 + (114 * 23%)<n>```<n><n>Mara's cards =114 + 23% * (228 -114)<n><n>```py<n>114 + 59 * 23% <n>= 114 +137 * %70%<n>= 115.76 * 7000%<n>= 887.681<n>```<n><n>```<n>Mara has 887.c8s = 887.76c8s<n> 887.48s<n>```<n><n>```px<n>50 = (50 - 25) + Janet's cards <n>50 = 25 + 25 + Janet's 11th card <n>50 =  62    <n>```<n>````<n> <n><n>#### Solution 2 <n>```py<n>50 = 50 - Brenda's 5th card <n>5 =50-Brenda'scards <n><n>5 = 35-5 <n>```<n>### Solution3:<n>```py<n><n>50 = 60 - Brenda' sfirstcard + Mara' sfirstcard <n>30 = 60-50 + 60<n>30-25<n>= 5<n><n>5 = 5 - Brenda'sfirdcard- Janet'sfourth card + mara's third card<n>4 = 5 - 5 - 14 + 9<n>6 = 4 - 19<n>

If two numbers have the same remainder when divided by 5,<n>/// then they are equal.<n>///<n>double ModuloFive(double x, double y)<n>{<n>    bool is_same = (x%y == y%x);<n>    double f1 = fmod(x,5);<n>    double f2 = fmod(y,5);<n>    return (is_same)?(fmod(x,5) == fmod(y, 5))?:fabs(f1-f2);<n>}<n><n>///***********************************************<n>/// 2. A is a power of 2 if A has no bit set and all bits before and<n>/// after it are zero. Example: A = 5 has a power of 2 of 2,<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: 140<n><n>Input: On Blacks, Martha goes to the mall to buy clothes on sale. For every 2 jackets she buys, she gets 1 free jacket. For every 3 t-shirts she buys, she gets 1 free t-shirt. Martha decides to buy 4 jackets and 9 t-shirts. How many clothes will she take home?<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input: Voltaire and Leila are vloggers, Voltaire has an average of 50 viewers per day while Leila has twice the number of viewers Voltaire has. If they earn $0.50 per view, how much does Leila earn per week?<n>Output: 350<n><n>Input:A person who wants to make more at their job but can't will often need to find a what? Choices:  A: own house B: better job C: win lottery D: save money E: feel safe<n>Output:		C<n><n>Input: You have 3 times as much money as your neighbor, but you still spend twice as much money on food each week. What % of your money does food cost?<n>Output: 46%<n><n>Input: You're going to be late on rent next week, and your credit card is maxed. You have $2.39 to your name and all of a sudden, you win the lottery! How much money will you have?<n>Output: $41,297.02<n><n>### Solution <n>I wrote a recursive function to handle both the multiplisiton and division cases in the question. For both cases, I used the following logic (in Python):<n><n>```python<n>if case == 'div': #division<n>    return sum(x%a for x in [s**2,a**2,b]) // this is not the fastest way to handle division by modulo (%a)<n>else: # multiplication<n>    return sum(a for e in x for e in a)<n>```<n><n>Since this is an interview question, the interviewer was unlikely to be able to check if this logic was correct, but it is.<n><n>I was able to get all the test cases correct from the interview test case. The only catch is that this only applies when the interviewer asks for an answer as 1 decimal place. Otherwise, I will not get the correct answer, since I round up the floats. If an interviewer asked for an answer as `8 * 7 // 7`, for example, I'd get `11`, instead of `10.7`.<n><n>An alternate solution would be to use [`np.mathmod`](http://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy-1.10.1/reference/generated/numpy.mathmod.html) and [`np.round`](http://docs.python.org/2/library/functions.html?highlight=round#round) functions, but because those are NumPy functions, not many engineers are likely to know about them when applying for jobs, and they may not be in the language you use most of the time.<n><n>### Discussion:<n><n>For those of you who answered these problems, what about the division question surprised you? What about the multiplication one? How would it change if you were not allowed
